[Transmission of WPV1 (wild poliovirus type 1) and cVDPVs (circulating vaccine derived polioviruses) is continuing. Pakistan confirmed 5 new cases in the past week, and in the past 24 hours another 5 were confirmed (see section [3] below. With respect to cVDPVs, 17 cases totalled from 5 countries (Nigeria, DR Congo, Angola, Ethiopia and the Philippines) were confirmed in the past week, and an additional 3 countries had positive environmental samples (Pakistan, Cote d'Ivoire and Somalia). Nigeria had a new focus for cVDPV2 with a case in Anambra state, the 1st confirmed case with onset in 2020. The Philippines confirmed an additional case in the past 24-48 hours from Nueva Ecija province, in Central Luzon, north of Manila (see section [2] below.

For a map showing the locations of both WPV-associated cases and cVDPV-associated cases, see http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

As done in previous posts, to visualize all of this activity, I am putting links to HealthMap/ProMED-mail maps of countries with poliovirus activity during the past 12-24 months below. The size of the list remains impressive, now with 25 countries: 16 in Africa, 5 in Asia, and 4 in the Western Pacific, with either WPV or cVDPV isolates in their countries. An important reminder is that positive environmental samples means that the virus is circulating in the area where the samples have been obtained. Hence, if a susceptible individual is infected with the virus, there is a chance the person may develop paralytic disease.

